data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":316,"item_id":"msg_0cd7aab1039f1d8c006918f928dae8819499a57698e282d795","output_index":1,"content_index":0,"text":"Do you mean in the context of nuclear power or chemical processing? “Steam reactor” can refer to two different things — I’ll summarize both briefly.\n\n1) Nuclear-power context\n- Informal name for a reactor system that produces steam to drive turbines. Examples:\n  - Boiling Water Reactor (BWR): reactor core boils the coolant and produces steam directly that goes to the turbine.\n  - Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR): core heats water under pressure; that hot primary water transfers heat in a steam generator to a secondary loop where steam is produced.\n- Key point: the reactor’s thermal energy is used to make steam that drives electric-generating turbines.\n- Main considerations: heat transfer, reactor control, radiation shielding, and safety systems to prevent and mitigate coolant loss or overheating.\n\n2) Chemical-process context\n- A reactor in which steam is a reactant or carrier gas. Common types:\n  - Steam reformer: steam reacts with hydrocarbons (e.g., methane) over a catalyst to produce synthesis gas (H2 + CO).\n  - Steam cracking furnaces: hydrocarbons are heated with steam to break them into smaller molecules (e.g., ethylene).\n- Key point: steam participates in chemical reactions or dilutes/carriers feedstock at high temperature.\n- Main considerations: catalysts, reaction kinetics, high-temperature materials, and process heat management.\n\nIf you tell me which meaning you intended (nuclear or chemical), I can give a more detailed explanation of how it works, components, or safety and operational issues.","logprobs":[]}

